25|$|In 1994, {{the court}} case Peloza v. Capistrano School District was decided against {{a teacher who}} claimed that his First Amendment right to free <b>exercise</b> <b>of</b> <b>religion</b> was {{violated}} by the school district's requirement to teach evolution.|$|E
25|$|The ruling {{went on to}} cite a U.S. Supreme Court {{decision}} {{which had}} held that if prohibiting the <b>exercise</b> <b>of</b> <b>religion</b> is merely the incidental effect of a generally applicable and otherwise valid provision, the First Amendment has not been offended.|$|E
25|$|Religious groups became {{concerned}} that this case would be cited as precedent for further regulation of common religious practices and lobbied Congress for legislative protection. RFRA provided a strict scrutiny standard, requiring narrowly tailored regulation serving a compelling government interest in any case substantially burdening the free <b>exercise</b> <b>of</b> <b>religion,</b> regardless of the intent and general applicability of the law.|$|E
